post_text:
Hurricane Laura has entered the Gulf of Mexico and models place the upper Texas coast in the storm’s path. While tracks may shift, the University of Houston, including UH at Katy and Sugar Land, will move instruction and services to online Wednesday, Aug. 26th through Friday, Aug. 28th.

There will be limited access to campus for research and other essential personnel Wednesday through Thursday. Those whose work allows them to work remotely and be fully functional should continue to do so. Supervisors are urged to provide flexibility for storm preparations. UH will continue to provide updates, including adjustments to Friday campus access or to the academic calendar, as warranted through the UH Alert system, www.uh.edu/emergency.

Make sure your emergency contact information is up to date in AccessUH and follow @UHalert on Twitter for updates to campus operations. https://alerts.uh.edu/update-contact-information/student-contact-updates/

Interim Graduate Grade Policy

post_text:
Due to the unique and unprecedented challenges associated with the COVID-19 pandemic, the University of Houston is implementing an interim policy for undergraduate grades.

Students have the option to choose Satisfactory/No Credit (S/NCR) grading on a course-by-course basis. The interim policy applies to all undergraduate students in courses offered during Spring 2020 Sessions 1, 4, 5, and 6 as well as the 2020 Summer Mini Session. The deadline for students to choose their grading option is 5 pm on May 18, 2020.
The University of Houston is taking these steps to help our students be successful during these current extraordinary circumstances.

More information is available here: https://uh.edu/provost/policies-resources/student/interim-undergraduate-grade-policy/index

post_text: University of Houston including UH at Katy and UH at Sugar Land will remain closed Friday, Sept. 20, through the weekend to allow our community to recover from today’s floods and due to uncertainties associated with weather and road conditions in the next 24 hours. UH will resume normal operations on Monday. Further updates will be posted on the UH ALERT System at www.uh.edu/emergency.
text: University of Houston including UH at Katy and UH at Sugar Land will remain closed Friday, Sept. 20, through the weekend to allow our community to recover from today’s floods and due to uncertainties associated with weather and road conditions in the next 24 hours. UH will resume normal operations on Monday. Further updates will be posted on the UH ALERT System at www.uh.edu/emergency.

post_text: UH including UH at Katy and UH at Sugar Land, has discontinued operations for the remainder of today due to worsening severe weather conditions throughout the Houston area. Shuttle service on and between campuses will continue to operate as conditions allow. On-campus services are open but may be limited. Anyone currently on campus is advised to remain here until conditions improve. Please use discretion and check Houston Transtar (https://traffic.houstontranstar.org/layers/) for roadway conditions. The University of Houston will continue to monitor this situation and advise on changes to operational status at www.uh.edu/emergency

post_text: UH including UH at Katy and UH at Sugar Land are continuing operations today. However, due to severe weather conditions throughout the Houston area and the unpredictable nature of this storm, students who are unable to attend class will not be penalized. Faculty and staff unable to attend work or class should contact their immediate supervisor. Anyone currently on campus is encouraged to remain here until conditions improve. If you must travel, use discretion and check Houston Transtar for roadway conditions. The University of Houston will continue to monitor this situation and advise on changes to operational status at www.uh.edu/emergency

Valenti School of Communication are teaming up with the nonprofit Recipe for Success Foundation to serve up a series of web videos about healthy eating. Aspiring filmmakers and photographers in the multimedia storytelling class are spending the semester honing their production skills at the nonprofit’s Hope Farms on Scott Street in Houston’s Sunnyside community. The series, “Chefs in the Field,” features area chefs who cook simple, healthy dishes using vegetables and herbs picked fresh from the farm.

#GoCoogs #Powerhouse

post_text:
Did you know?

Cougars in Recovery provides a safe and sober environment for students in recovery from addiction. CIR is open to all UH undergraduate and graduate students who are currently in recovery and seeks to support them in their academic and collegiate experience.

Through weekly Community Check-ins, social and service events, along with Outdoor Adventure Learning Experiences, CIR has become a home to many students on our campus.

To learn more, visit http://bit.ly/2xT3HOX
